3.4 Discrete Specialization
When pre-defined domains are available (e.g., medicine, law, finance), each interaction is classified into top- domains via soft assignment against domain centroids. This produces separate transition matrices , each row-stochastic, capturing the fraction of interactions between agents relevant to domain . The per-domain iteration is:
This is the key structural difference from TSPR: where TSPR uses the same for all topics and varies only the teleportation vector, TrustFlow uses different per domain. When agent calls agent for a medical task, this edge appears with high weight in and low weight in . TSPR cannot make this distinction.
Each per-domain iteration is an independent PageRank with domain-specific structure, converging in iterations (approximately 11 for , ) (Langville and Meyer 2006).
Continuous vs. discrete. The discrete formulation requires a pre-defined domain taxonomy and cannot represent cross-domain expertise without dilution. A biostatistics agent must split its reputation mass across medicine and data-science bins. The continuous formulation eliminates this bottleneck: a 384-dimensional vector can simultaneously align with both domain centroids. The discrete formulation is a specialization of the continuous one—obtained by replacing the embedding space with a domain indicator space and the content-gated transfer with domain-conditioned matrices.
